'''Friedrich "Fritz" Kreisler''' (February{{nbsp}}2, 1875{{snd}}January{{nbsp}}29, 1962) was an [[Austria]]n-born [[violin]]ist and [[composer]].<ref name=obit /> One of the most noted violin masters of his day, and regarded as one of the greatest violin masters of all time, he was known for his sweet [[Musical tone|tone]] and expressive [[Musical phrasing|phrasing]]. Like many great violinists of his generation, he produced a characteristic sound which was immediately recognizable as his own. Although it derived in many respects from the Franco-Belgian school, his style is nonetheless reminiscent of the ''[[gemütlich]]'' (cozy) lifestyle of pre-war [[Vienna]].

== Biography ==
Kreisler was born in [[Vienna]], the son of Anna (her original Hebrew name, listed in her sons’ birth certificates was "Chaje Riwe" (rendered as "Chaje Ribe" in Hugo's record) (née Reaches) and Samuel Kreisler, a doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UvG8FTMhCyAC&pg=PA456|title=Jüdisches biographisches Lexikon: eine Sammlung von bedeutenden Persönlichkeiten jüdischer Herkunft ab 1800|first=Hans|last=Morgenstern|date=1 January 2009|publisher=Lit|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nEbX3O9cWaoC&q=Anna%20Reches%20Samuel%20Kreisler&dq=Anna%20Reches%20Samuel%20Kreisler&source=bl&ots=_6GrA06fxA&sig=30TqJi5mvHxFzgv49QqBxTvfV2w&hl=en&redir_esc=y|title=Freud, Appraisals and Reappraisals: Contributions to Freud Studies|first=Paul E.|last=Stepansky|date=1 January 1986|publisher=Analytic Press|isbn=0-88163-038-1|via=Google Books}}</ref> Of Jewish heritage, he was however [[Baptism|baptised]] at the age of 12. He studied at the [[University of Music and Performing Arts, Vienna|Vienna Conservatory]] and in Paris, where his teachers included [[Anton Bruckner]], [[Léo Delibes]], [[Jakob Dont]], [[Joseph Hellmesberger Jr.]], [[Joseph Massart]], and [[Jules Massenet]]. While there, he won the "Premier Grand Prix de Rome" gold medal at the age of 12, competing against 40 other players, all of whom were at least 20 years of age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/fritz-kreisler-mn0000757095/biography|title=Fritz Kreisler – Biography & History – AllMusic|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>

He made his United States debut at the [[Steinway Hall]] in [[New York City]] on November 10, 1888, and his first tour of the United States in 1888–1889 with [[Moriz Rosenthal]]. He then returned to Austria and applied for a position in the [[Vienna Philharmonic]], but was turned down by the concertmaster [[Arnold Rosé]]. As a result, he left music to study medicine. He spent a brief time in the [[army]] before returning to the violin in 1899, when he gave a concert with the [[Berlin Philharmonic]] conducted by [[Arthur Nikisch]]. It was this concert and a series of American tours from 1901 to 1903 that brought him real acclaim.

In 1910, Kreisler gave the premiere of Sir [[Violin Concerto (Elgar)|Edward Elgar's Violin Concerto]], a work commissioned by and dedicated to him. He served briefly in the Austrian Army in [[World War I]] before being honourably discharged after he was wounded. He arrived in [[New York City|New York]] on November 24, 1914,<ref>{{cite news |title=The world of music |url=https://archive.org/stream/independen79v80newy#page/420/mode/1up |newspaper=The Independent |date=Dec 14, 1914 |accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref> and spent the remainder of the war in America. He returned to Europe in 1924, living first in Berlin, then moving to France in 1938.  Shortly thereafter, at the outbreak of [[World War II]], he settled once again in the United States, becoming a [[naturalized citizen]] in 1943. He lived there for the rest of his life, giving his last public concert in 1947, and broadcasting performances for a few years after that.

[[File:Fritz Kreisler, Harold Bauer, Pablo Casals, and Walter Damrosch at Carnegie Hall on March 13, 1917.jpg|thumb|left|Fritz Kreisler, [[Harold Bauer]], [[Pablo Casals]], and [[Walter Damrosch]] at [[Carnegie Hall]] on March 13, 1917]]
On April 26, 1941, he was involved in a serious traffic accident. Struck by a truck while crossing a street in New York, he suffered a fractured skull and was in a coma for over a week.<ref>[[Life (magazine)|''Life'' magazine]], May 12, 1941 (pp. 32–33)</ref>

In his later years, he suffered from not only some hearing loss but also sight deterioration due to cataracts.<ref>Fritz Kreisler: Love's Sorrow, Love's Joy, by Amy Biancolli (Amadeus Press, 1998)</ref>

Kreisler died of a heart condition aggravated by old age in New York City in 1962.<ref name=obit>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/01/30/archives/fritz-kreisler-dies-here-at-86-violinist-composed-200-works-made.html |title=Fritz Kreisler Dies Here at 86; Violinist Composed 200 Works; Made His U.S. Concert Debut in 1888 at 13. Was Known for His Arrangements |newspaper=New York Times|quote=Fritz Kreisler, the world-famous violinist and composer, died yesterday. He would have been 87 years old on Friday. ... |date=January 30, 1962 |accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> He was interred in a private mausoleum in [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]], [[The Bronx]], New York City.

== Legacy ==
Kreisler wrote a number of pieces for the violin, including solos for encores, such as "[[Liebesleid]]" and "[[Liebesfreud]]". Some of Kreisler's compositions were [[pastiche]]s ostensibly in the style of other composers.  They were originally ascribed to earlier composers, such as [[Gaetano Pugnani]], [[Giuseppe Tartini]] and [[Antonio Vivaldi]], and then,  in 1935, Kreisler revealed that it was he who wrote the pieces. When critics complained, Kreisler replied that they had already deemed the compositions worthy: "The name changes, the value remains", he said. He also wrote [[operetta]]s, including ''Apple Blossoms'' in 1919<ref>[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011813210 Catalog Record for the vocal score of Apple Blossoms]</ref> and ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Sissy (operetta)|de|3=Sissy (Operette)|lt=Sissy}}'' in 1932, a [[string quartet]], and [[cadenza]]s, including ones for [[Violin Concerto (Brahms)|Brahms's D major violin concerto]], [[Niccolò Paganini|Paganini]]'s [[Violin Concerto No. 1 (Paganini)|D major violin concerto]], and [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s [[Violin Concerto (Beethoven)|D major violin concerto]]. His cadenzas for the Beethoven concerto are the ones most often played by violinists today.

He wrote the music for the 1936 movie ''[[The King Steps Out]]'' directed by [[Josef von Sternberg]], based on the early years of [[Empress Elisabeth of Austria]].

Kreisler performed and recorded his own version of the first movement of Paganini's D major violin concerto. The movement is rescored and in some places reharmonised, and the orchestral introduction is completely rewritten in some places. The overall effect is of a late-nineteenth-century work.

[[File:The Mausoleum of Fritz Kreisler in Woodlawn Cemetery.JPG|thumb|The mausoleum of Fritz Kreisler in [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]]]]
Kreisler owned several antique violins made by [[luthier]]s [[Antonio Stradivari]], [[Pietro Guarneri]], [[Giuseppe Guarneri]], and [[Carlo Bergonzi (luthier)|Carlo Bergonzi]], most of which eventually came to bear his name.
He also owned a [[Jean-Baptiste Vuillaume]] violin of 1860, which he often used as his second violin,<ref>[http://www.maestronet.com/m_library/world_strings/fall80.pdf  Second Fiddle by Philip Kass]</ref> and which he often loaned to the young prodigy [[Josef Hassid]]. In 1952 he donated his Giuseppe Guarneri to the Library of Congress in Washington, D.C. where it remains in use for performances given in the library.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200155594/|title=Violin by Giuseppe Guarneri, Cremona, ca. 1730, "Kreisler"|website=loc.gov}}</ref>

On recordings, Kreisler's style resembles that of his younger contemporary [[Mischa Elman]], with a tendency toward expansive [[Tempo|tempi]], a continuous and varied [[vibrato]], expressive [[Musical phrasing|phrasing]], and a melodic approach to passage-work. Kreisler makes considerable use of [[portamento]] and [[rubato]]{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}. The two violinists' approaches are less similar in big works of the standard repertoire, such as [[Felix Mendelssohn]]'s [[Violin Concerto (Mendelssohn)|Violin Concerto]], than in smaller pieces.

A trip to a Kreisler concert is recounted in [[Siegfried Sassoon]]'s 1928 [[autobiographical novel]] ''[[Memoirs of a Fox-Hunting Man]]''.

