{{Infobox writer | name = Rachel Louise Snyder | occupation = Journalist | genre = non-fiction; novel | image = RLS Author Photo.jpg }}
'''Rachel Louise Snyder''' is an American journalist, writer, and professor. She covers domestic violence and previously worked as a foreign correspondent for [https://www.marketplace.org/2008/01/29/business/big-book/how-many-countries-are-your-jeans Marketplace] and also contributed to All Things Considered, on NPR and This American Life.
A story she reported for This American Life<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/archive|title=Archive - This American Life|work=This American Life|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref> won an Overseas Press Award, along with [[Ira Glass]] and [[Sarah Koenig]].
Her work has appeared in the ''New York Times'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/search/sitesearch/?action=click&contentCollection=Opinion&region=TopBar&WT.nav=searchWidget&module=SearchSubmit&pgtype=Blogs#/RACHEL%2520LOUISE%2520SNYDER/since1851/allresults/1/allauthors/newest/|title=RACHEL LOUISE SNYDER - NYTimes.com Search|last=|first=|date=|website=query.nytimes.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref> the ''New Yorker'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/07/22/a-raised-hand|title=A Raised Hand|last=Snyder|first=Rachel Louise|date=2013-07-15|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2017-12-21|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> the ''Washington Post'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/which-domestic-abusers-will-go-on-to-commit-murder-this-one-act-offers-a-clue/2017/11/16/80881ebc-c978-11e7-aa96-54417592cf72_story.html|title=Perspective {{!}} Which domestic abusers will go on to commit murder? This one act offers a clue.|last=Snyder|first=Rachel Louise|date=2017-11-16|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-21|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> and ''Slate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wins.penfaulkner.org/author/rachel-louise-snyder|title=Rachel Louise Snyder {{!}} Writers in Schools {{!}} PEN/Faulkner Foundation|website=wins.penfaulkner.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref> She lived in London, Cambodia, and Washington, DC and is originally from Chicago.
== Works == * ''Fugitive denim: a moving story of people and pants in the borderless world of global trade'', New York; London: W.W. Norton, 2009. {{ISBN|9780393335422}}, {{OCLC|286487649}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/mar/29/society|title=Review: Fugitive Denim by Rachel Louise Snyder|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|date=2008-03-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> * ''What We've Lost Is Nothing.'', New York: Scribner, 2014. {{ISBN|9781476725178}}, {{OCLC|857568212}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/what-weve-lost-is-nothing-by-rachel-louise-snyder/2014/01/23/6c996a6c-8121-11e3-bbe5-6a2a3141e3a9_story.html|title=‘What We’ve Lost Is Nothing,’ by Rachel Louise Snyder|last=See|first=Carolyn|date=2014-01-23|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-21|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/review-what-we-ve-lost-is-nothing-by-rachel-louise-snyder/242850201/|title=Review: 'What We've Lost is Nothing,' by Rachel Louise Snyder|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref>
